{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512113"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:50:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:50:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11840"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11840"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.23,0.7,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4441"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51515"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4441"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11840"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36816"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6408"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7636"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14807"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51515"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of gradually worsening colicky flank pain. The pain is most intense in the right lumbar region and radiates inferiorly to the groin. He has noticed blood in his urine since yesterday. He has been very nauseated and has vomited twice today. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 130/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His mucous membranes are dry. There is right renal angle tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urine microscopy and culture","Ultrasound KUB","Non-contrast CT KUB","Abdominal X-ray","Urine dipstick"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs highly suggestive of nephrolithiasis, including unilateral colicky flank pain radiating to the groin, associated with nausea, vomiting, and haematuria. Given this clinical picture, imaging is required to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-contrast CT KUB\u003C/strong\u003E (CT urogram) is the most appropriate diagnostic test for suspected renal stones. It has the highest sensitivity (97%) and specificity (95%) for detecting renal calculi among all imaging modalities. It can accurately identify the size, location, and number of stones, as well as any associated complications such as hydronephrosis or perinephric abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound KUB\u003C/strong\u003E is less sensitive than CT in detecting renal tract calculi, particularly ureteric stones. While it may be the initial imaging modality of choice in pregnant women or when CT is unavailable, it is not the most reliable test for confirming nephrolithiasis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E can detect radiopaque stones and provide information about their location. However, its sensitivity (29-59%) is much lower than that of CT KUB. It may miss radiolucent stones and provides less detailed information about the surrounding structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E are important parts of the workup for suspected urinary tract infection, which can coexist with renal stones. However, they are not diagnostic for nephrolithiasis itself and do not provide information about stone characteristics or location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine dipstick\u003C/strong\u003E can detect haematuria and signs of infection, which are common in renal stone disease. However, like urine microscopy and culture, it is not diagnostic for nephrolithiasis and does not provide information about stone characteristics or location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile all these investigations may be part of the overall assessment, non-contrast CT KUB remains the gold standard for diagnosing nephrolithiasis due to its superior sensitivity and specificity, as well as its ability to provide detailed information about stone characteristics and associated complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-contrast CT KUB is the most sensitive and specific imaging test for diagnosing nephrolithiasis.","Consider nephrolithiasis in patients presenting with unilateral colicky flank pain associated with nausea, vomiting and/or haematuria."],"references":["Kidney stones in adults: diagnosis and acute management of suspected nephrolithiasis. In: UpToDate [Online]. 2022 [cited 2022 Oct 18]. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/kidney-stones-in-adults-diagnosis-and-acute-management-of-suspected-nephrolithiasis","Nojaba L, Guzman N. Nephrolithiasis. In: Statpearls [Online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559227/","Brisbane W, Bailey MR, Sorensen MD. An overview of kidney stone imaging techniques. Nat Rev Urol. 2016 Nov;13(11):654-662. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5443345/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36816"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11840"}}